Here are the definitions and example codes for Day 4 as a fresher:

HTML Concepts:
1. HTML Styles:
Definition: HTML styles are used to add visual effects to HTML elements.

Example Code:

<p style="color: blue; font-size: 24px;">This text is blue and 24px in size.</p>

2. HTML Semantic Elements:
Definition: HTML semantic elements are used to define the structure of a web page, making it easier for search engines and screen readers to understand.

Example Code:

<header>This is the header section</header>
<nav>This is the navigation section</nav>
<main>This is the main content section</main>
<footer>This is the footer section</footer>

CSS Concepts:
1. CSS Introduction:
Definition: CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a styling language used to control the layout and appearance of web pages.

2. CSS Syntax:
Definition: CSS syntax consists of selectors, properties, and values.

Example Code:

p {
  color: blue; /* property: value */
  font-size: 24px; /* property: value */
}

3. CSS Selectors:
Universal Selector ()*
Definition: The universal selector is used to select all elements on a web page.

Example Code:

* {
  margin: 0; /* apply margin to all elements */
  padding: 0; /* apply padding to all elements */
}

ID Selector (#id)
Definition: The ID selector is used to select a specific element with a unique ID.

Example Code:

<p id="my-paragraph">This is a paragraph.</p>



#my-paragraph {
  color: red; /* apply color to element with ID "my-paragraph" */
}

Class Selector (.class)
Definition: The class selector is used to select elements with a specific class.

Example Code:

<p class="my-class">This is a paragraph.</p>
<p class="my-class">This is another paragraph.</p>



.my-class {
  color: green; /* apply color to elements with class "my-class" */
}



HTML Q&A:
1. *Q: What is the purpose of the <style> attribute in HTML?*
A: The <style> attribute is used to add styles to an HTML element.
2. Q: What is the difference between HTML semantic elements and non-semantic elements?
A: HTML semantic elements provide meaning to the structure of a web page, while non-semantic elements do not.
3. Q: What is an example of an HTML semantic element?
A: The <header> element is an example of an HTML semantic element.

CSS Q&A:
1. Q: What is the purpose of CSS?
A: CSS is used to control the layout and appearance of web pages.
2. Q: What is the basic syntax of CSS?
A: The basic syntax of CSS consists of selectors, properties, and values.
3. *Q: What is the difference between the universal selector (*) and the ID selector (#id)?*
A: The universal selector (*) selects all elements on a web page, while the ID selector (#id) selects a specific element with a unique ID.